Pacific herring (Clupea pallasii) as a key forage fish in the southeastern Gulf of Alaska

https://doi.org/10.1016/j.dsr2.2021.105001Get rights and content

Abstract

Pacific herring (Clupea pallasii) is a schooling planktivorous fish consumed by numerous fish, seabirds, and marine mammals. This paper aimed to determine whether Pacific herring serves as a key forage fish (i.e. strongly supports predator populations) in the southeastern Gulf of Alaska. All analyses were conducted using mass- and energy-balanced ecosystem models constructed in Ecopath with Ecosim. Supportive Role to Fishery (SURF) index values were computed using predator diets and food web structure encoded in static ecosystem models. Ecosystem impacts of herring stock depletion and collapse were evaluated using quantitative criteria (thresholds) applied to dynamic ecosystem simulations. SURF index values from mass-balanced models lay below the threshold required to designate herring as a key forage fish. However, values from an energy-balanced model supported the key status of herring. Dynamic ecosystem simulations in mass- and energy-balanced models revealed strong negative effects of herring depletion on several predators. In most energy-balanced models, simulation results designated herring as a key forage fish despite indications of functional redundancy in the forage fish guild. Impacts of herring depletion on predators were stronger and more numerous in energy-balanced models, suggesting that the high energy content of herring enhances its importance to predators. Simulation results also demonstrated positive impacts of herring depletion on two zooplankton groups due to release from predation pressure. The status of Pacific herring as a key forage fish apparently depends on its energy content relative to other forage fish. Nevertheless, the results of this study support precautionary, ecosystem-based management of Pacific herring fisheries.

1. Introduction

Forage fish (i.e. small, schooling planktivores) form narrow trophic conduits channeling energy from zooplankton to higher predators, including diverse piscivorous fish, seabirds, and marine mammals (Cury et al., 2011, Smith et al., 2011, Pikitch et al., 2012a,b; Engelhard et al., 2014). The unique importance of forage fish to these predators is likely reinforced (Litzow et al. 2004, 2006; Spitz et al. 2010a, 2012, 2018) by the elevated energy content of forage fish relative to most other fish and invertebrates (Perez 1994; Anthony et al., 2000; Vollenweider et al., 2011; Spitz et al., 2010b; Spitz and Jouma'a 2013). Furthermore, numerous industrial, artisanal, aboriginal, and subsistence fisheries target forage or piscivorous fish, thereby relying, directly or indirectly, on forage fish productivity (Pikitch et al., 2012a,b, Engelhard et al., 2014). Thus, metrics derived from static ecosystem models and food web structure (PlagÃ¡nyi and Essington 2014) as well as from dynamic ecosystem simulations (Smith et al., 2011) have been devised to identify key forage fish, i.e. species providing particularly strong support for predators and fisheries.
The main aim of this paper is to determine whether Pacific herring (Clupea pallasii) functions as a key forage fish in the southeastern Gulf of Alaska ecosystem. In a global analysis investigating the importance of forage fish to predators (and thus to fisheries targeting them) using the novel SUpportive Role to Fisheries (SURF) index based on static food web structure and validated with dynamic ecosystem simulation, 27 forage stocks belonging to five families (Clupeidae, Engraulidae, Osmeridae, Ammodytidae, and Scombridae) were identified as key in 17 ecosystems worldwide (PlagÃ¡nyi and Essington 2014). These stocks included Pacific herring in Prince William Sound but not the west-central Gulf of Alaska, Hecate Strait, or Puget Sound.
Some forage fish, particularly in upwelling ecosystems, have been suggested to exhibit â€œwasp-waistâ€ dynamics, i.e. simultaneously exert top-down control on prey and bottom-up control on predators (Cury et al., 2000). However, the high degree of omnivory displayed by numerous marine predators (Madigan et al., 2012) and the apparent redundancy in the forage fish guilds of many ecosystems (Bundy and GuÃ©nette 2014) have cast doubt on this hypothesis. Nevertheless, forage fish apparently exert top-down control on zooplankton in some cases (Cury et al., 2000) and are controlled by them in a bottom-up fashion in others (Engelhard et al., 2014). Relatively strong evidence exists of forage fish exercising bottom-up control over numerous predators, particularly central place foragers and mobile species forming large feeding aggregations (Smith et al., 2011, Pikitch et al., 2012a,b; Engelhard et al., 2014). These groups include most seabirds (Cury et al., 2011; Hannesson 2013; Sydeman et al., 2017a), numerous marine mammals (e.g. McClatchie et al., 2016a, MarÃ§alo et al., 2018, Giralt et al., 2021, Tsagarakis et al., 2021), and piscivorous fish (e.g. Kaplan et al., 2017; Koehn et al., 2017). Thus, exploiting forage fish may impair the trophic support they provide to charismatic and fished predators (Pikitch et al., 2012a,b; Smith et al., 2011), especially for key forage fish (PlagÃ¡nyi and Essington 2014), although this effect may be reversed by high predator fishing mortality (Soudijn et al., 2021). Prey switching by predators exhibiting the sigmoid Type III functional response (Holling 1959), along with the functional redundancy characterizing forage fish guilds in many ecosystems (Bundy and GuÃ©nette 2014), may buffer the adverse impacts of exploiting forage fish on predator populations (Hilborn et al., 2017; Free et al., 2021). However, simple predator-prey models suggest that these buffering mechanisms may fail due to recruitment limitation in both forage and piscivorous fish, allowing efficient piscivores to inflict depensatory mortality on exploited forage fish (Walters et al., 2016).
Forage fish are also characterized by an r-selected life history including high fecundity and natural mortality, short lifespan, and early maturation (Pikitch et al., 2012b). These traits, combined with the close link between forage fish stock status and bottom-up oceanographic drivers, produce high-amplitude fluctuations in forage fish biomasses on interannual to multidecadal scales (McClatchie et al., 2017; Trochta et al., 2020). Such fluctuations, which may be intensified by depensatory predation mortality (Walters et al., 2016; Jacobsen and Essington 2018), render forage fish particularly susceptible to stock collapses (McClatchie et al., 2017; Trochta et al., 2020), especially when stock assessment models overestimate biomass in less productive years, resulting in ineffective management and excessive fishing mortality (Pinsky and Byler 2015; Essington et al., 2015). Furthermore, due to their schooling behaviour, forage fish are prone to depensatory increases in catchability, which also promote stock collapses (Pitcher 1995). This vulnerability of forage fish to exploitation, combined with their apparent importance to numerous fished, protected, and charismatic predators (Smith et al., 2011, Pikitch et al., 2012a,b; Engelhard et al., 2014), has stimulated global calls for precautionary, ecosystem-based management of these prey species (Stephenson 1997, Smith et al., 2011, Pikitch et al., 2012a,b) and lends particular importance to the identification of key forage fish. However, several recent studies question the importance of forage fish to predators and thus the need for changes to existing fisheries management practices (Hilborn et al., 2017; Free et al., 2021).
Pacific herring is a large, long-lived forage fish inhabiting the coastal North Pacific from the Yellow Sea to the California Current (Hay et al., 2008). Off the central coast of British Columbia (Canada), it preys on diverse zooplankton including copepods, pelagic amphipods, euphausiids, pteropods, and ichthyoplankton (Pakhomov et al., 2017). In the Northeast Pacific, including the Gulf of Alaska, herring is an important prey species for numerous commercial fish (Brodeur et al., 2014; Osgood et al., 2016; Chamberlin et al., 2021) and seabirds (Schrimpf et al., 2012; Bishop et al., 2015; Sydeman et al., 2017b; Drever et al., 2021) as well as many marine mammals, including humpback whales (Megaptera novaeangliae; Boswell et al., 2015, Moran et al., 2018; Straley et al., 2018) and Steller sea lions (Eumetopias jubatus; Gende and Sigler 2006; Womble and Sigler 2006; Sigler et al., 2017). Most of these marine mammals and seabirds are protected under the United States Endangered Species Act, Migratory Bird Treaty Act, or Marine Mammal Protection Act.
Due to its importance to these predators, Schweigert et al. (2010) consider herring the principal forage fish in British Columbia waters, while Fox et al. (2015, 2018) identify it as a foundation species. Like keystone species, foundation species interact strongly within the food web, but unlike keystone species, they are often highly abundant (SoulÃ© et al., 2003). Pacific herring is also an important forage fish in the California Current (Szoboszlai et al., 2015) as far south as San Francisco Bay (Thayer et al., 2020). The forage role of Pacific herring is especially strong and taxonomically extensive during the spring spawning season, when both fish and roe sustain a diverse coastal predator guild (Willson and Womble 2006; Lok et al., 2012, Thayer et al., 2020). Furthermore, its high energy content relative to most other forage and non-forage fish as well as invertebrates in the Gulf of Alaska (Perez 1994; Anthony et al., 2000; Vollenweider et al., 2011) likely renders herring an especially desirable prey species. The only coastal Northeast Pacific forage fish consistently exceeding herring in energy content is eulachon (Thaleichthys pacificus), an anadromous smelt formerly abundant and important as salmon prey but now much less abundant than herring (Osgood et al., 2016). This suggests that numerous predators in the southeastern Gulf of Alaska may rely on herring for substantial fractions of their energetic demands (Surma et al., 2018a). Thus, Pacific herring is a potentially key forage fish.
However, the directions and magnitudes of trophic interactions between Pacific herring and its predators have only recently begun to be studied in depth. Schweigert (1997) detected minor but significant improvements in Ricker stock-recruitment model fits to data for northern British Columbia stocks of Pacific cod (Gadus macrocephalus), chinook salmon (Oncorhynchus tshawytscha), and rock sole (Lepidopsetta bilineata) upon including herring abundance as a predictor, with the weak impacts on these predators likely due to functional redundancy in the forage fish guild. In the Gulf of Alaska, the latter also includes Pacific sandlance (Ammodytes personatus) and various smelts (Osmeridae), notably Pacific capelin (Mallotus catervarius). Schweigert et al. (2010) observed a paradoxical negative correlation between consumption by predators and total natural mortality in herring off the west coast of Vancouver Island, perhaps indicating density-dependent effects. Mounting evidence suggests that recovering humpback whales may exert top-down control over Northeast Pacific herring (Ford et al., 2009; Heintz et al., 2010; Surma and Pitcher 2015; Boswell et al., 2015; Moran et al., 2018; Straley et al., 2018). A recent ecosystem modelling study (Surma et al., 2019) detected multiple strong interactions of both signs between herring and its predators and prey in the southeastern Gulf of Alaska.
Numerous commercial, aboriginal, and subsistence fisheries in the Gulf of Alaska exploit Pacific herring directly or rely on it to support piscivorous fish stocks (Pikitch et al., 2012a,b), including lingcod (Ophiodon elongatus), Pacific salmon (Oncorhynchus spp.) and rockfish (Sebastes spp.). Zooarchaeological data reveal that local aboriginal peoples have depended on abundant herring (McKechnie et al., 2014, Moss et al., 2016) and piscivorous fishes (McKechnie and Moss 2016) for millennia prior to first contact. Herring continues to play important subsistence and cultural roles for the Heiltsuk (Gauvreau et al., 2017), GitxaaÆša (Menzies 2016, ch. 6), Haida (Jones et al., 2017), and Tlingit (Thornton et al., 2010; Moss et al., 2011).
However, in recent years, the depressed status of many Pacific herring stocks from Alaska to California has raised increasing concern among scientists (Cleary et al., 2010; Schweigert et al., 2010; Pearson et al., 2012; Thompson et al., 2017), management agencies (NMFS 2014; DFO 2015; Kronlund et al., 2018), and aboriginal peoples (Thornton et al., 2010; Jones et al., 2017; Gauvreau et al., 2017). It has also stimulated the latter to advocate for increased precaution and transparency in herring fisheries management, despite repeated assertions in analyses conducted by management agencies (Haist et al. 1986, 1993; Hall et al., 1988; Zheng et al., 1993; Funk and Rowell 1995; Cleary et al., 2010) that the status quo is precautionary enough, at least from a single-species perspective. Neither bottom-up nor top-down control alone has conclusively explained the depression of these stocks, although both of these mechanisms are likely involved along with non-trophic factors (Schweigert et al., 2010; Pearson et al., 2012; NMFS 2014). For example, in Prince William Sound, freshwater runoff and density-dependence (Ward et al., 2017), pathogens (Marty et al., 2003), the 1989 Exxon Valdez oil spill (Thorne and Thomas 2008; Incardona et al., 2015), and increased predation by recovering humpback whales (Moran et al., 2018; Straley et al., 2018) may all have been contributing factors. In any case, the importance of herring to aboriginal and commercial fisheries and the depression of many stocks in the Gulf of Alaska underscore the acute need for improved knowledge of the trophic interactions linking this potentially key forage fish to its numerous predators. Identification of Pacific herring as a key forage fish would support precautionary, ecosystem-based, and ethical management of Northeast Pacific herring fisheries (Surma et al., 2018b; Lam et al., 2019).

2. Materials and methods

2.1. Ecosystem models

This study utilized two previously published (Surma et al., 2019) mass-balanced models built in Ecopath with Ecosim (EwE; Christensen and Walters, 2004), one of the most commonly used ecosystem modelling frameworks (Coll et al., 2015). These models represented the southeastern Gulf of Alaska ecosystem states existing in historical (1950) and recent (2000â€“2015) periods, respectively. The models were designed to quantify the trophic role of herring during the period a) of high finfish and low marine mammal abundance in the mid-20th century and b) following the finfish declines and marine mammal recoveries of the late 20th century (Surma et al., 2019).
This study also employed seven energy-balanced EwE models representing the recent state of the southeastern Gulf of Alaska ecosystem. These models were designed to account for the enhanced importance of herring to numerous predators (Surma et al., 2018a) due to its high energy content relative to most other prey (Perez 1994; Anthony et al., 2000; Vollenweider et al., 2011). Each energy-balanced model was constructed using the recently developed method of rescaling basic mass-balanced Ecopath model parameters (biomass, tâ‹…kmâˆ’2; consumption per biomass, yrâˆ’1; and diet composition) with published energy content values (kJâ‹…gâˆ’1 wet weight; Appendix B, Table B1) for all functional groups. The first two models employed the highest and lowest published energy content values for each group, respectively, while the remaining five were derived from energy content values randomly resampled from uniform distributions bounded by the highest and lowest values (Appendix B, Table B2). The fundamental principles of EwE and the energy-balanced modelling method (Surma et al., 2018a) are summarized in Appendix A, while basic parameters for all energy-balanced models are provided in Appendix B (Tables B3-B9).
The recent mass-balanced model was selected as the basis for all energy-balanced models to avoid the assumption that recent energy content values (Perez 1994; Anthony et al., 2000; Vollenweider et al., 2011) are applicable to the historical model. This assumption is put into question by documented density-dependent declines (e.g. Casini et al., 2006) and oceanographically driven fluctuations (e.g. Siddon et al., 2013; Suryan et al., 2021) in forage fish energy content. The decision to base the energy-balanced models on the recent mass-balanced model required the likewise questionable assumption that vulnerability parameter values obtained from fitting the historical mass-balanced model to time series may be utilized in models representing the recent ecosystem state (Ainsworth et al., 2008). For the purpose of comparisons between mass- and energy-balanced models, however, the impacts of this assumption on the credibility of Ecosim outputs are mitigated by the fact that identical vulnerabilities were employed in the mass- and energy-balanced models.

2.2. Static ecosystem analyses

Due to its detailed qualitative and quantitative representation of static food web structure, the SUpportive Role to Fishery (SURF) index (PlagÃ¡nyi and Essington 2014) was employed as the first metric assessing the support provided to predators by herring, and hence its importance as a forage fish, in the southeastern Gulf of Alaska. According to PlagÃ¡nyi and Essington (2014):SURF=âˆ‘j=1Spij2Lwhere S is the number of predators j in the food web, pij is the fraction of prey i in the diet of predator j, and L is the number of links in the food web. Thus, unlike connectance (i.e. the number of trophic links to a forage fish/ total number of food web links), utilized by an earlier study (Smith et al., 2011) to assess forage fish importance to predators, SURF quantitatively evaluates predator dependence on forage fish (PlagÃ¡nyi and Essington 2014). Furthermore, SURF is less sensitive than connectance to the common ecosystem modelling practice of aggregating multiple predators into single functional groups (PlagÃ¡nyi and Essington 2014). Based on a comparison of SURF scores with metrics derived from dynamic simulations using multiple EwE models, SURF = 0.001 was adopted as the approximate threshold for key forage fish status (PlagÃ¡nyi and Essington 2014).
Herring SURF was calculated and compared across all mass-balanced and energy-balanced EwE models of the southeastern Gulf of Alaska ecosystem. In these calculations, all four local herring stocks (Haida Gwaii, Haida Gwaii 2 West, Prince Rupert District, and Central Coast) and all three age/size classes (age 0, age 1â€“2, and age 3+) represented in the models were considered together. Thus, overall herring pij was calculated as âˆ‘k=1npkj, where n = 12 is the number of herring groups k in the models, while in calculating L all links between the n herring groups and each prey i or predator j were counted as single links. SURF was also computed and compared across all models for the three other forage fish functional groups, i.e. forage fish (primarily sandlance and smelts, including capelin), Pacific saury Cololabis saira, and eulachon.

2.3. Dynamic ecosystem simulations

Impacts of simulated herring depletion on predators provided the second metric of the forage role of herring in the southeastern Gulf of Alaska. For herring to be classified as a key forage fish (PlagÃ¡nyi and Essington 2014) based on simulation results, the impacts of 60% herring depletion (i.e. reduction to 40% of unfished biomass), would have to include A1) a decline â‰¥70% in at least one functional group or B) declines of 40â€“69% in at least 10% of predators (i.e. groups with trophic level â‰¥3). The weaker criterion A2, derived from an earlier study (Smith et al., 2011), employed a slightly lower threshold than A1 (a decline â‰¥60% in at least one group).
Simulation methods were based on those employed in a pilot study (Surma et al., 2018b) but utilized improved food web models with increased functional group resolution for seabirds, invertebrates (zooplankton and benthos), and benthic producers, as well as a new fit to time series (Surma et al., 2019). As in the pilot study, all Ecosim runs lasted 100 simulated years and a scenario (#1) representing herring fisheries closure (F = 0) served as a baseline. Unlike in the pilot study, however, another Ecosim scenario (#2) simulating 60% depletion of adult herring (ages 3+) was run to yield simulation metrics of key forage fish status (Smith et al., 2011; PlagÃ¡nyi and Essington 2014). As in the pilot study, the final scenario (#3) represented herring stock collapse (i.e. 95% depletion). All three Ecosim scenarios were evaluated across all mass- and energy-balanced models. Unlike in the pilot study, in scenarios #2 and #3 fishing mortality was only increased for adult herring. The reasons for this were twofold. Firstly, recent catches of juvenile herring (age 1â€“3) in the southeastern Gulf of Alaska were negligible (as the roe fishery dominant since the early 1970s exclusively targets pre-spawners). Secondly, the models suggest that adult herring were most heavily consumed by predators. A substantial majority of spawning herring in the study area have, until very recently, been age 3+ (Schweigert et al., 2010). Fishing mortalities for all other functional groups remained at baseline levels (Surma et al., 2019) across all scenarios.
In order to generate realistic trends in potential ecosystem change and account for impacts of top-down and bottom-up forcing simultaneous with herring depletion, two sets of time series were employed in all scenarios, as in the pilot study (Surma et al., 2018b). Firstly, time series representing reconstructed and projected biomass trajectories of five historically depleted whale species (i.e. humpback, blue Balaenoptera musculus, fin B. physalus, sei B. borealis, and sperm Physeter macrocephalus) were utilized to simulate whale population recoveries and evaluate their ecosystem impacts across all mass- and energy-balanced models. Previous simulations indicate these effects may be substantial in the southeastern Gulf of Alaska (Surma and Pitcher, 2015), suggesting the need to include them in other ecosystem simulations. Whale abundance reconstructions and projections were derived from surplus production models (Surma 2019) based on historical whaling catches (Nichol and Heise 1992), recent abundance estimates, and annual population rates of increase for each species, following the basic approach described in Surma and Pitcher (2015). Abundances were converted to biomasses using species-specific average individual masses (Trites and Pauly 1998). Whale biomass time series drivers were deactivated in one of two Ecosim runs for each scenario to evaluate possible bottom-up impacts of herring availability on whale populations. For energy-balanced models, whale biomass (tâ‹…kmâˆ’2) time series were converted to energy (Jâ‹…mâˆ’2) using the energy content (kJâ‹…gâˆ’1) values provided in Appendix B, (Table B1). Otherwise, all Ecosim scenarios were run identically across the recent mass- and energy-balanced models.
Secondly, in the historical model, bottom-up effects of stochastic interannual variability in primary productivity were represented in Ecosim by a phytoplankton biomass time series. The 1950â€“2015 time series utilized to fit the model and generate hindcasts (Surma et al., 2019) was extended by 100 years through randomized resampling with repetition from a phytoplankton biomass dataset for 1950â€“2000 (Ainsworth et al., 2008). All whale and phytoplankton time series employed in this study are provided in supplementary file S1. In the historical model, in order to correctly represent fisheries and ecosystem dynamics up to and including the scenario start time, historical fishing mortality trends were imposed on all exploited functional groups until 2015 (Surma et al., 2019), whereupon the baseline, depletion, and collapse simulations (i.e. scenarios #1-3) were initialized.

3. Results

3.1. Static ecosystem analyses

Herring SURF index values for each model appear in Fig. 1. In the mass-balanced models (historical and recent), herring SURF did not exceed 0.001, the key forage fish status threshold (PlagÃ¡nyi and Essington 2014). In five out of seven energy-balanced models (#1, #2, #4, #6, and #7), herring SURF surpassed 0.0005 but lay below the key status threshold. However, in one energy-balanced model (#3), herring SURF exceeded 0.001, thus narrowly meeting the key forage fish status requirement. For the forage fish group, SURF surpassed the key status threshold in all models. For saury and eulachon, SURF lay below 0.001 across all models.

3.2. Dynamic ecosystem simulations

Simulation results (Fig. 2, Fig. 3, Fig. 4) revealed notable differences in key forage fish status metrics for herring between scenario #2 (depletion) and scenario #3 (collapse), as well as between recent mass- and energy-balanced models. Key forage status criterion A1 (at least one functional group decline â‰¥70%; PlagÃ¡nyi and Essington 2014) was satisfied in scenario #3 (collapse) but not in scenario #2 (depletion) by both mass-balanced models (historical and recent), as well as three energy-balanced models (#4â€“6). However, the threshold for criterion A1 was attained in both scenarios by the remaining four energy-balanced models, yielding majority support for herring key status among energy-balanced models. With model #3 (which employed extremely high herring energy content values) excluded, half of the energy-balanced models classified herring as key under criterion A1. The weaker key status criterion A2 (at least one group decline â‰¥60%; Smith et al., 2011) was satisfied in scenario #3 (collapse) but not in scenario #2 (depletion) by both mass-balanced models, although it was very nearly met by the recent model in scenario #2 (Fig. 3). However, the threshold for criterion A2 was exceeded in both scenarios by all energy-balanced models (Fig. 3, Fig. 4). Key forage status criterion B (40â€“69% declines in â‰¥10% of predators; PlagÃ¡nyi and Essington 2014) was not satisfied by any model in either scenario, despite at least one predator decline of 40â€“69% occurring in all models and scenarios except the historical mass-balanced model in scenario #2 (Fig. 2, Fig. 3, Fig. 4).
The identity of the predators most negatively impacted by reduced herring availability, and thus responsible for herring meeting the criteria for key forage fish status, varied among scenarios and models (Fig. 2, Fig. 3, Fig. 4). Humpback whales surpassed the threshold for criterion A1 (70% decline) in the recent mass-balanced model (scenario #3, Fig. 4) and four energy-balanced models (scenarios #2 and #3, Fig. 3, Fig. 4). Minke whales (B. acutorostrata) and inshore rockfish (i.e. copper rockfish S. caurinus, quillback rockfish S. maliger, tiger rockfish S. nigrocinctus, China rockfish S. nebulosus, and yelloweye rockfish S. ruberrimus) crossed this threshold in the historical mass-balanced model (scenario #3, Fig. 2). Minke whales exceeded the threshold for criterion B (60% decline) in all energy-balanced models (scenario #3, Fig. 4), while humpback whales crossed this threshold in all energy-balanced models (scenarios #2 and #3, Fig. 3, Fig. 4) and very nearly attained it in the recent mass-balanced model (scenario #2, Fig. 3).
Some functional group responses differed in sign among scenarios or models. In the historical mass-balanced model, nearly all functional groups responding with declines â‰¥10% to herring collapse (scenario #3) responded with biomass increases to herring depletion (scenario #2), except for carnivorous jellyfish and small gelatinous zooplankton (Fig. 2). In the recent mass-balanced model, such a change in response sign from negative to positive was only found in shallowwater benthic fish (Fig. 3, Fig. 4). Consistently positive responses (â‰¥10%) to herring depletion and collapse occurred across all models for macrozooplankton, amphipods, forage fish, walleye pollock Gadus chalcogrammus, Pacific cod G. macrocephalus, and seals (Fig. 2, Fig. 3, Fig. 4).
In addition, several herring predators (sea lions, piscivorous seabirds, coho salmon O. kisutch, Pacific hake Merluccius productus, and arrowtooth flounder Atheresthes stomias) responded positively (by â‰¥ 10%) to herring depletion (scenario #2, Fig. 3) and collapse (scenario #2, Fig. 4) in the recent mass-balanced model but reacted negatively across all energy-balanced models. Furthermore, for three marine mammal functional groups reliant on herring directly (small odontocetes) or indirectly (resident and transient orcas Orcinus orca), responses to both scenarios were positive (â‰¥10%) in the recent mass-balanced model but negative when averaged across energy-balanced models, although 95% confidence intervals around the mean responses included zero. Finally, in six herring predator groups (humpback, fin, and minke whales, inshore rockfish, lingcod, and blue sharks Prionace glauca), negative responses to both scenarios (â‰¥10%) intensified in energy-balanced models relative to the recent mass-balanced model, while positive responses strengthened in only three functional groups (sperm whales, walleye pollock, and shallowwater benthic fish).

4. Discussion

4.1. Static ecosystem analyses

The SURF index provided only limited support for the status of herring as a key forage fish in the southeastern Gulf of Alaska. Neither the historical nor recent mass-balanced model yielded SURF values for herring indicating key status (PlagÃ¡nyi and Essington 2014). This result agrees with those obtained by the original SURF analysis from Ecopath models for Hecate Strait, west-central Gulf of Alaska, Aleutian Islands, and Puget Sound (PlagÃ¡nyi and Essington 2014) and only conflicts with its finding for Prince William Sound. It also accords with the finding yielded by an earlier version of the recent mass-balanced model (Lam et al., 2019). However, one energy-balanced model (#3) produced a SURF value suggesting key forage fish status for herring. This result can be explained by the extremely high energy content values for adult herring (9â€“10 kJâ‹…gâˆ’1) compared to those for the forage fish group (4 kJâ‹…gâˆ’1) in model #3. Nevertheless, five of seven energy-balanced models yielded SURF values for herring less than half an order of magnitude below the threshold. This suggests that herring is more likely to qualify as a key forage fish when the high energy content of adult herring relative to other Northeast Pacific prey species (Perez 1994; Anthony et al., 2000; Vollenweider et al., 2011) is considered. This finding agrees with that of a recent study (Surma et al., 2018a) regarding the enhanced importance of herring to predators due to its elevated energy content. The key status of the aggregated forage fish group across all models can be explained by its high biomass, and in the absence of species-specific biomass estimates it is uninformative regarding the key status (or lack thereof) of its constituent species.

4.2. Dynamic ecosystem simulations

Simulation results revealed some notable discrepancies among the outcomes of different criteria for key forage fish status as applied to herring. The SURF index (PlagÃ¡nyi and Essington 2014) was the most conservative metric, with only one energy-balanced model parameterized with extreme energy content values supporting key status for herring (Fig. 1). Dynamic criterion A1 (PlagÃ¡nyi and Essington 2014), classifying herring as key in most energy-balanced models (half if the extreme model was excluded), was intermediate between SURF and the most liberal criterion B (Smith et al., 2011), which accorded herring key status in all energy-balanced models. Surprisingly, a key status threshold of SURF = 0.0005 would align better with dynamic criterion A1 than the original value of 0.001 (PlagÃ¡nyi and Essington 2014), with seven of nine models yielding the same binary result for herring (i.e. key or not) using both metrics. This finding is notable since the original global analysis establishing the SURF index, which included 65 forage fish stocks and 24 Ecopath models, never ranked a stock as key based on criterion A1 but not on SURF = 0.001, with these metrics thus yielding identical results (PlagÃ¡nyi and Essington 2014).
Furthermore, in the dynamic ecosystem simulations of herring depletion (scenario #2, Fig. 3), the key forage fish status of herring invariably resulted from exceptionally strong impacts on a single predator (the humpback whale). While the related minke whale also responded to herring depletion with declines of â‰¥40%, criterion A2 for key forage fish status (PlagÃ¡nyi and Essington 2014), which requires declines of 40â€“69% in â‰¥10% of predators, was not met by the response of any model to herring depletion (Fig. 3). These results indicate that even when herring emerges as a key forage fish, the trophic impacts of herring depletion in the southeastern Gulf of Alaska are moderated by food web complexity and forage fish guild redundancy. While four groups of predators (humpback and minke whales, inshore rockfish, and lingcod) exhibited the expected negative responses to simulated herring depletion in the mass-balanced models, six others (small odontocetes, seals, sea lions, piscivorous seabirds, hake, and arrowtooth flounder) demonstrated surprising positive responses.
These results can be explained by the release of three planktivorous fish functional groups (walleye pollock, saury, and especially forage fish) from exploitation competition for limiting primary and secondary production due to herring depletion. This release, combined with the dynamic specification of diet compositions in Ecosim (Christensen and Walters 2004), allowed biomasses of six herring predators to increase despite decreased herring biomass. Furthermore, three top predators (resident orcas, transient orcas, and salmon sharks Lamna ditropis) benefited indirectly from increased biomasses of non-herring planktivorous fish through their positive bottom-up effects on the small marine mammals and salmon consumed by these top predators. Diets of all four herring predator groups responding negatively to herring depletion contained higher proportions of herring than of the aggregated forage fish group, while the opposite was true of the predators responding positively (except for hake, which, however, also benefited from the release of euphausiids from herring predation). These results indicate that the contributions of a given forage fish (e.g. herring) to predator diets relative to the shares of other forage fish in these diets, rather than the absolute proportions of a given forage fish employed in the SURF index (PlagÃ¡nyi and Essington 2014), may better predict predator responses to forage depletion.
These findings agree with those of an early ecosystem simulation analysis (Mackinson et al., 1997) regarding the consequences of forage fish depletion, i.e. direct negative effects on some predators, increased zooplankton and planktivorous competitor biomass, and resulting indirect positive impacts on other predators. They also accord with the adverse impacts of forage fish depletion on predators frequently detected in two global studies (Smith et al., 2011, Pikitch et al., 2012a,b). More specifically, negative impacts of herring depletion on humpback and minke whales, as well as planktivorous rockfish (Sebastes spp.), were likewise observed in an EwE model of the California Current ecosystem adjoining the Gulf of Alaska to the south (Koehn et al., 2017). Ecosystem models of the southeastern Gulf of Alaska and California Current also agree in emphasizing the roles of food web complexity and forage fish guild redundancy in modulating the impacts of herring depletion on predators (Kaplan et al. 2013, 2017; Koehn et al. 2016, 2017). In the California Current, simulated forage fish depletion in both EwE and Atlantis positively affected some zooplankton and planktivorous fish through release from predation and competition, respectively (Kaplan et al. 2013, 2017). These releases resulted from generalist feeding by most predators and functional redundancy among forage fish (Koehn et al., 2016; Kaplan et al., 2017). However, it should be noted here that herring accounts for a much lower proportion of total forage fish biomass in the California Current (Koehn et al., 2016) than in the southeastern Gulf of Alaska (Surma et al., 2019). Nevertheless, an ecosystem simulation study of the importance of Atlantic menhaden (Brevoortia tyrannus), a key forage fish in Chesapeake Bay (PlagÃ¡nyi and Essington 2014), to predators in the Northwest Atlantic off the east coast of the United States (Buchheister et al., 2017) yielded similar findings.
While herring did not emerge as a key forage fish in the mass-balanced model simulations, it was classified as such based on simulation results from most energy-balanced models (criterion A1). These results indicate that herring depletion could affect numerous predators more adversely than suggested by the corresponding mass-balanced model (Fig. 3). These predators include endothermic piscivorous seabirds and marine mammals (humpback, minke, and fin whales, sea lions, and small odontocetes) as well as ectothermic fish (inshore rockfish, lingcod, blue sharks, hake, coho salmon, and arrowtooth flounder). These results agree with recent findings regarding the high metabolic demands of small odontocetes and their resulting preference for energy-rich forage fish (Spitz et al. 2010a, 2012, 2018; MarÃ§alo et al., 2018; Rojano-DonÃ£te et al., 2018, Tsagarakis et al., 2021). They also accord with conclusions on analogous energetic drivers of seabird (Litzow et al., 2004) and sea lion (Trites and Donnelly, 2003) foraging ecology, and the consequent association between energy-rich forage fish availability and breeding success in numerous seabirds (Litzow et al., 2004; Anchundia et al., 2014; Divoky et al., 2015) and sea lions (Trites and Donnelly 2003; McClatchie et al., 2016a; Banuet-MartÃ­nez et al., 2017), as well as Brandt's cormorant (Phalacrocorax penicillatus) colony size in the central California Current (Ainley et al., 2018). Finally, these findings support the hypothesis that the high energy content of forage fish (Engelhard et al., 2014) such as Pacific herring (Surma et al., 2018a) could intensify the impacts of their depletion on predators. However, this hypothesis is somewhat complicated by observations that although many active, endothermic predators (e.g. small penguins) selectively hunt energy-rich prey, they also consume low-energy species (e.g. scyphozoan jellyfish and ctenophores) even in the presence of preferred, energy-rich resources (Thiebot et al., 2017; Hays et al., 2018). In southeast Alaska, low-energy prey (e.g. walleye pollock) can contribute substantially to Steller sea lion diet if sufficient high-energy prey (e.g. herring) are also ingested (Sigler et al., 2009). In the Northeast Pacific, humpback whale net energy gain from consumption of relatively energy-poor but slow-swimming krill can exceed that from energy-rich but faster-moving herring or northern anchovy (Engraulis mordax) if krill aggregations are dense enough (Chenoweth et al., 2021, Savoca et al., 2021).
Nevertheless, it is noteworthy that the southeastern Gulf of Alaska food web responded strongly to simulated herring collapse (scenario #3), with herring meeting criterion A1 for key forage fish status in this scenario across all ecosystem models (Fig. 2, Fig. 4). The frequency and severity of herring stock collapses worldwide (Trochta et al., 2020) highlight the importance of these results. Furthermore, recent studies cast doubt on the ability of functional redundancy in forage fish guilds, and competition among their members, to buffer the bottom-up impacts of individual forage fish declines on higher trophic levels. Firstly, the intense marine heatwave of 2014â€“2016 in the Gulf of Alaska triggered rapid and synchronous declines in Pacific herring and capelin biomass, as well as Pacific sandlance energy content, through acute bottom-up impacts on prey quality, with severe and widespread repercussions for seabirds, marine mammals, and large fish deprived of sufficient energy-rich prey (Arimitsu et al., 2021; Suryan et al., 2021). Secondly, a global analysis determined that multidecadal fluctuations in sardine and anchovy biomasses, long considered asynchronous, exhibit more complex dynamics with the potential to disrupt their hypothesized buffering effect on predator responses to forage fish declines (Siple et al., 2020).
Thus, the findings of the present study and other recent analyses highlight the need for a cautious approach to the supposed buffering of adverse impacts on predators by functional redundancy in forage fish guilds (Walters et al., 2016). They also support calls for precautionary, ecosystem-based fisheries management for forage fish in general (Smith et al., 2011; Pikitch et al., 2012a,b, 2018) and Pacific herring in the southeastern Gulf of Alaska in particular (Surma et al., 2018a,b; Surma et al., 2021; Lam et al., 2019). In addition, these findings disagree with those of several recent studies questioning the importance of forage fish to predators (Hilborn et al., 2017; Free et al., 2021).
The ecosystem simulation results of the present study are burdened with several caveats and limitations. Firstly, any errors in EwE parameters derived from inputs or fits to time series (Surma et al., 2019) may affect simulation outputs through multiple pathways, including predator functional responses. Secondly, the common practice of aggregating species (e.g. forage fish or seabirds) into functional groups in ecosystem models may mask negative effects of depleting specific forage fish (e.g. Pacific sardine Sardinops sagax) on specialist predators (e.g. brown pelicans Pelecanus occidentalis; Punt et al., 2016; Kaplan et al., 2019). Thirdly, the lack of a high-resolution representation of spatiotemporal overlap between predators and prey in an ecosystem model may obscure the importance of fine-scale variability in forage fish biomass to central place foragers such as pinnipeds and seabirds (Koehn et al., 2017; Sydeman et al., 2017a). For example, in southeast Alaska, persistent herring aggregations provide crucial feeding areas for Steller sea lions (Gende and Sigler 2006). Fourthly, the absence of an explicit age-structured representation of predatory fish biomass (except for Pacific halibut Hippoglossus stenolepis) may lead ecosystem simulations to overestimate the strength of trophic responses to forage fish depletion (Forrest et al., 2015; Walters et al., 2016; Kaplan et al., 2017). Fifthly, the lack of a model representation of seasonality in predator diets, e.g. due to fluctuating herring availability (Willson and Womble 2006; Womble and Sigler 2006) and energy content (Anthony et al., 2000; Vollenweider et al., 2011), may affect ecosystem simulation results. Finally, the use of a scenario (#1) with fisheries closed for one species (i.e. herring) but open for all others as a â€œbaselineâ€ may yield a release of herring biomass not reflecting a true ecosystem baseline, in which unfished predators could absorb much of the likewise unfished herring biomass through top-down control.
In addition, the ecological importance of herring may have decreased over time due to depletion by commercial fisheries. High herring biomass in the southeastern Gulf of Alaska circa 1950, as represented in the historical mass-balanced model (Surma et al., 2019), would likely have ranked herring as a key forage fish once its high energy content was incorporated into such a model. Furthermore, while estimated annual biomasses (DFO 2015) and carrying capacities (Perry and Schweigert 2008) based on stock assessments extend no further than 1951, zooarchaeological data indicate that herring abundance in the Northeast Pacific declined steeply since the onset of commercial fisheries in the 19th century (McKechnie et al., 2014), suggesting that its ecological importance may have also decreased. However, eulachon, a forage fish with an energy content exceeding even that of herring (Perez 1994; Anthony et al., 2000; Vollenweider et al., 2011), is also more heavily depleted, raising the intriguing question of the relative significance of these two species in Northeast Pacific ecosystems prior to commercial fishing (Osgood et al., 2016).
When analyzed across all models, depletion simulation results support the hypothesis that a mosaic of top-down and bottom-up control characterizes herring trophic interactions in the southeastern Gulf of Alaska (Surma et al., 2019). Mass- and energy-balanced models indicate that herring exerts strong bottom-up effects on humpback and minke whales as well as inshore rockfish. Furthermore, energy-balanced models suggest that herring biomass may also have notable bottom-up impacts on blue sharks, lingcod, Pacific hake, coho salmon, and perhaps piscivorous seabirds, sea lions, and small odontocetes. Bottom-up effects of herring availability on many predators agree with the findings of previous studies on the trophic roles of forage fish (Smith et al., 2011, Pikitch et al., 2012a,b; Engelhard et al., 2014). The substantial proportion of fish among predators apparently supported by herring accords with the results of these analyses, but not the conclusions of others suggesting that mammals and particularly seabirds are most heavily dependent on forage fish (Hannesson 2013; Hilborn et al., 2017). Simulation results from all models also indicate top-down control by herring over two omnivorous zooplankton groups (macrozooplankton and amphipods). These findings agree with observed top-down effects of other forage fish on zooplankton (Cury et al., 2000; Engelhard et al., 2014).
At first glance, this pattern of bottom-up impacts of herring on predators and top-down effects on prey is reminiscent of the â€œwasp-waistâ€ trophodynamics proposed for other forage fish (Cury et al., 2000). However, previous studies (Heintz et al., 2010; Surma and Pitcher 2015; Boswell et al., 2015, Moran et al., 2018; Straley et al., 2018) indicate that recovering humpback whales could exert top-down impacts on herring in the Gulf of Alaska. Furthermore, network analysis (mixed trophic impacts) and ecosystem hindcasts conducted using the historical mass-balanced model (Surma et al., 2019) suggest that herring biomass is also subject to bottom-up effects of variable primary and secondary productivity (phytoplankton and copepods, respectively). This finding, together with the competition among planktivorous fish detected in the present study, agrees with bottom-up control of the productivity of commercial fish in general (Ware and Thomson 2005) and herring in particular (Perry and Schweigert 2008) in the Northeast Pacific, as well as forage fish productivity in the North Sea (Engelhard et al., 2014). Thus, Pacific herring trophodynamics appears to be substantially more intricate than the â€œwasp-waistâ€ hypothesis would suggest. In addition, this hypothesis has been more generally criticized as an oversimplification of forage fish trophodynamics in complex food webs (Madigan et al., 2012; Bundy and GuÃ©nette 2014).

5. Conclusions

The analyses presented in this study lead to several conclusions. Firstly, Pacific herring may function as a key forage fish in the southeastern Gulf of Alaska when its energy content is high relative to those of other forage fish. Secondly, herring biomass supports numerous predators, including piscivorous fish, marine mammals, and seabirds. Thirdly, bottom-up impacts of herring availability on these predators may be partly damped by functional redundancy within the forage fish guild. Fourthly, however, these bottom-up effects of herring on many predators are likely intensified by the high energy content of herring relative to other prey in the Gulf of Alaska. Fifthly, herring can exert top-down impacts on omnivorous zooplankton. Finally, similarities between herring trophodynamics and the â€œwasp-waistâ€ hypothesis appear superficial.
The findings of this study indicate that the demand of predators for herring should be included in a comprehensive perspective on its ecology. These results support the need for precautionary, ecosystem-based fisheries management strategies in Northeast Pacific herring fisheries (Surma et al., 2018b, Surma et al., 2021). Furthermore, given the demonstrated capacity of climate-driven seasonal and interannual shifts in energy-rich zooplankton abundance to reduce the biomass or energy content of pelagic fish in the Gulf of Alaska (Arimitsu et al., 2021; Suryan et al., 2021) and throughout the Northeast Pacific (Mackas et al., 2007; Hunt et al., 2011; Heintz et al., 2013; Siddon et al., 2013; McClatchie et al., 2016b), the calls for ecosystem-based fisheries management for such species gain strength and urgency from increasingly frequent marine heatwaves and global climate change (Di Lorenzo and Mantua 2016; Alexander et al., 2018; Cheung and FrÃ¶licher 2020).
